In honor of National Colorectal Cancer Awareness Month, Melania and Donald Trump express their support for those fighting colon and rectal cancer. They also offer condolences to the families and friends of those who have lost their lives to this disease. Colorectal cancer is the second leading cause of cancer-related deaths in the United States, and individuals over the age of 50, with a family history of colorectal cancer, or from African-American or Hispanic backgrounds are at a higher risk. The Trump administration is committed to providing resources for medical professionals and research institutions to combat colorectal cancer. They are focused on accelerating advancements in medical technology, clinical trials, and treatments through the 21st Century Cures Act. The administration also encourages regular screenings for those at higher risk and aims to improve the quality of care for those battling the disease. The article recognizes the efforts of researchers, medical professionals, and public health officials in developing treatments, providing care, and promoting screening programs. The Trumps join those diagnosed with cancer and their loved ones in praying for a future free from cancer.